history.content:
189 is more along the lines of traditional math! Focus on linear algebra and vector calculus; there will be mathematically rigorous proofs and so forth; you will probably find it better compared to 170. Be warned though, there is a heavy amount of programming in 189, so you do need to know how to write code on an equivalent of finishing 61B level (at least in my estimate). 

Keep in mind: I took with Shewchuk this spring; Sahai is teaching in the Fall and I do not know how he will change the curriculum.

I am an Applied Math major, who has additionally taken some classes in the CS department. I took 188 and 170 this past semester, and did well in both, although I found 170 immensely challenging: although I've written proofs in math classes, they were certainly different from the ones I did in 170...170 seemed to require a different style of thinking, as well as knowing a lot of common tricks that show up often, to do the problems.

I am enrolled in 189 for the fall. For people who have taken both 189 and 170, (and of course, professors), could you please give me some advice on whether the types of proofs/problems in 189 are like the ones we see in 170? or are 189 problems more along the lines of "traditional" math problems? sorry if this question is a bit vague...i just thought that 170 was very different from any kind of math i've seen before. hopefully people understand what i'm getting at. thank you!
history.subject: 189 vs 170?
